From 156a58fd109fb86269559a98a5e3ad5cd7c3bbcc Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Tommy van der Wal <tommy@it-launch.nl>
Date: Mon, 27 Apr 2026 14:07:07 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] lock/fast: shared lock fast-path bypasses stale
 writers-waiting flag
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

A second 3-node EC:1 failure mode surfaces after the dsync read-quorum
fix: even with read_quorum=1, individual shared-lock attempts on
specific objects time out at the 5 s acquire_timeout. Both surviving
lock clients (including the **local** one on the requesting node)
return `LockResult::Timeout` for the slow path.

Root cause: a stale `WRITERS_WAITING_MASK` bit in the local atomic
lock state, left over by a slow-path exclusive-lock waiter whose
parent task was cancelled (typically because the peer that initiated
the lock RPC died mid-flight). The cancellation skips
`dec_writers_waiting()` at shard.rs:194-195, so the counter never
returns to zero. Subsequent shared-lock attempts on that object see
"writers waiting", fail their fast path, queue behind the phantom
writer, and time out.

The fix lets the shared-lock fast path proceed when only the
WRITERS_WAITING bit is set (no actual exclusive holder). Shared locks
are mutually compatible with each other by design — multiple readers
are an explicit invariant of the API — so accepting concurrent
readers ahead of a queued writer does not change the meaning of the
shared/exclusive contract. The exclusive-lock acquire path is
unchanged: writers still require a fully-unlocked state
(COMPLETELY_UNLOCKED).

Trade-off accepted: writer fairness on hot objects under sustained
read load. Acceptable for the small-cluster, mostly-read tier this
lock is on; the proper upstream fix should address the leak at the
slow-path waiter cancellation site (always dec_writers_waiting on
Drop).

Validated: 360 reads + 10 writes across all 6 victim/endpoint
permutations on a 3-node sim cluster, every node taken down in turn,
== 100 % success. Pre-patch: ~91 % (4 hard failures clustering on
specific objects whose lock state had stale writer-waiting flags).

This bug is NOT 3-node-specific in nature — same leak path exists
upstream on 4+ node clusters; it's just less likely to manifest
because more peers stay healthy and reconverge faster.

Companion to the dsync read-quorum patch (commit c1686a3).

Signed-off-by: Tommy van der Wal <tommy@it-launch.nl>
---
 crates/lock/src/fast_lock/state.rs | 18 ++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 14 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/crates/lock/src/fast_lock/state.rs b/crates/lock/src/fast_lock/state.rs
index 2896ead..1fcf0ed 100644
--- a/crates/lock/src/fast_lock/state.rs
+++ b/crates/lock/src/fast_lock/state.rs
@@ -66,8 +66,11 @@ impl AtomicLockState {
         let state = self.state.load(Ordering::Relaxed); // Use Relaxed for better performance
         match mode {
             LockMode::Shared => {
-                // No writer and no waiting writers
-                (state & NO_WRITER_AND_NO_WAITING_WRITERS) == 0
+                // Only block on an actual writer holding the lock. Stale
+                // "writer waiting" flags from dead peers are deliberately
+                // ignored here — see try_acquire_shared() for the full
+                // rationale. Shared locks are mutually compatible.
+                (state & WRITER_FLAG_MASK) == 0
             }
             LockMode::Exclusive => {
                 // Completely unlocked
@@ -83,8 +86,15 @@ impl AtomicLockState {
         loop {
             let current = self.state.load(Ordering::Acquire);
 
-            // Fast path check - cannot acquire if there's a writer or writers waiting
-            if (current & NO_WRITER_AND_NO_WAITING_WRITERS) != 0 {
+            // Fast path check - cannot acquire if there's an actual writer holding
+            // the lock. We deliberately do NOT block on WRITERS_WAITING here:
+            // shared locks are mutually compatible (multiple readers allowed by
+            // design), and stale "writer waiting" flags from a peer that died
+            // without releasing would otherwise pin the resource until cleanup
+            // (default 30 s). Writer starvation under sustained read load is
+            // possible but acceptable for the small-cluster, mostly-read tier
+            // this lock is on.
+            if (current & WRITER_FLAG_MASK) != 0 {
                 return false;
             }
 
